<br>
Kyri look at the troll guards found outside the harbor of Dulak. The journey was nearly completed after the unusual experience of actually having to walk a good ways to get here. It seems the portals in the Plane of Knowledge had forgotten about this spot when they set up their mystical passages. Nonetheless the journey was at an end. <br>
<br>
As she reached into her pouch she took out the letter which offered her free passage to her soon to be employer- something necessary in this place where even others who trod the dark paths were scowled at by the pirates of the harbor. Still a writ of safe passage from one of the five Captains would be enough to ensure her safety for now. None of the pirates would risk interfering with their work.<br>
<br>
Still the job itself was rather oddly discovered. In one of her rare trips to Cabilis, Kyri found a posting in the Haggle Baron which caught her attention. A Captain Osaftars from Dulak’s Harbor sought out an assassin to remove some competition- of course this Osaftars didn’t come out and say that of course, but in her line of work Kyri knew how to read between the lines. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Odd that’s he’d post here.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought to herself at first <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>After all the iksar aren’t really into the assassination business, they just prefer to march out in force and obliterate everyone in their way. Doesn’t make much sense to post something like this here. Unless he wanted to make sure someone who wasn’t an enemy of Cabilis found it.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She concluded deciding to check with the Baron himself.<br>
<br>
The Baron of course, like most of the city residents, gazed down on Kyri distastefully as she hailed him. Being polite, since he was in the position to let her make some money, Kyri used the Baron’s own tongue which failed to impress him but he grudgingly deigned to speak with her. The Baron had assured Kyri that the letter was indeed genuine and the job a real one. Of course like any merchant he professed his innocence of any knowledge of what lay behind the note. “I am a trader softskin,” he had told her “I hear much but nothing that will get me killed, that’s bad business. Even you softskins should know that.” He had replied when pressed for more details.<br>
<br>
The Baron then began to turn away before stopping and turning back to Kyri, taking a piece of paper out of a pocket. “If you DO wish to take this mission, I have been instructed to give you this seal of passage, in Captain Osaftars’ own writing, to ensure you reach him without getting killed. You softskins ARE rather fragile I have seen. I hope you read our language better than you speak it, if you doubt my words, read it for yourself.” He sneered with a hiss placing the paper on the table before him.<br>
<br>
Opening the folded paper Kyri read, slowly as the iksar tongue was not something she had seen many books written in but she managed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>“The bearer of this pass is to be left alone by any harbor dweller for the bearer is here at MY request and WILL be allowed to meet me on the Stormwave at port. Interfere at your own peril.<br>
<br>
In my own hand,<br>
Osaftars- Captain of the Stormwave<br>
Council of the Five &lt;seal&gt; ”</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
“Council of the Five?” Kyri asked, “What is that?”<br>
<br>
“Softskin…” The Baron replied annoyed, “If you wish to have answers go to the harbor and find them. I was paid to post the offer and give any who expressed interest this note. I know or care nothing else about the matter. Now I have much more important business to take care of than dealing with a softskin like you so be off now.” He finished pointedly turning his back on Kyri and leaving the room.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Well I guess I’ll find out how well this works, at least the pay will be good, and assassinations always pay well, even if I have to deal with this sort of annoyance.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought to herself as she neared the gate guards to the harbor who scowled as she approached them. Taking out the pass, while keeping her hands from her weapons, Kyri held the note out idly wondering if the troll guard could even read. As if to answer her suspicions the troll looked at it oddly, and then passed it to its fellow guard, who looked at it equally confused, though both pointed to the seal at the bottom of the letter, the seal of the Council.<br>
<br>
Then the first troll, looked back to the guardhouse and whistled. Turning back to Kyri, the troll said surprising Kyri with its plain speech,” I don’t read this tongue but I know the seal. Sergeant should clear this up.” The troll said normally as Kyri reflected to the rumors that the trolls here weren’t your average roll around in the mud and think its fun types. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Guess the stories were right.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She decided as another figure approached an iksar she saw surprised to see these two races working together rather harmoniously it seemed at first glance.<br>
<br>
“What is it?” the Sergeant said as he arrived, then looked to Kyri- “you two need help taking this one in?” gesturing dismissively at Kyri with his thumb.<br>
<br>
“No sarge,” the first troll replied, “she had this note from the Council- but we can’t read it so figured you might.”<br>
<br>
“What letter from the Council?” the sergeant demanded as he took the note and skimmed it quickly. Then turning to Kyri he said a bit more respectfully. “Ah I see you DO have business here. Don’t let me keep you.” He said standing aside to let her pass.<br>
<br>
“The note.” Kyri said holding out her hand.<br>
<br>
The sergeant looked at her in apparent surprise that the note of passage was still in his claws. “Oh of course, here you go.” He apologized handing the note back to her.<br>
<br>
“What you though I’d let you hold onto this so the next person I run into around the corner can jump me because you have it?” Kyri said taking the note back. “If you’ll excuse me, we can’t keep the Council waiting after all can we? What’s your name sergeant, I’d be happy to tell the Council how helpful you were to me?” She finished smiling.<br>
<br>
“Um, that won’t be necessary,” the sergeant stammered, the LAST thing he wanted was for the Council to take notice of him, especially if he interfered with one of their jobs. People didn’t get to do so a second time he had seen. Turning around sharply, he began to berate the two trolls for their slovenly appearance hoping that this stranger would be gone when he turned back around. To his relief she was.<br>
<br>
Well finding the dock won’t be hard, just follow my nose. Kyri concluded as the smell of the sea, fish and garbage filled the air. Twice more she was forced to show her pass to some wandering guards before she found the dock itself. Checking into one of the inns there, she carefully stored her belongings and put her own special locks on the door and windows- just in case, as it WAS a port town and being too comfortable usually meant you left with nothing you walked in with except the shirt on your back- if you were lucky.<br>
<br>
Once her room was secured to her satisfaction, Kyri made her way towards the docks themselves where she found five large ships in port. Quickly she made the connection- <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>the Council of Five must be the captains of these ships, a sort of pirate’s guild I guess</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> she determined as she made her way down the docks. Naturally she started on the wrong side and made her way down the entire dock before finding the Stormwave at the end of the docks. Walking up the dock ramp towards the ship she saw two iksar immediately come to attention drawing their shivs ready to toss this intruder off their ship.<br>
<br>
Sighing to herself, Kyri again brought forth the note which, the pirate read and said. “Come this way, the Cap’n has been waiting for someone to arrive for some time.” Taking their place at either side the two guards, escorted Kyri onto the ship, though their closeness to her made Kyri feel as if she was a prisoner being sent out under guard. Soon enough they made their way to the main deck and up to a door to a room on the deck. “Cap’n’s quarters, wait here.” The first guard instructed as he softly knocked on the closed door, a muffled voice could be heard within and the iksar went inside.<br>
<br>
Shortly Kyri’s escort came out of the room with another iksar- this one bearing the air of command about him, and more importantly to Kyri, was bearing a small chest. Bearing his teeth in what was supposed to be a smile the newcomer greeted Kyri, “Ah excellent, I had thought the Baron was going to let me down. I am Captain Osaftars, come inside where we can discuss the matter you’re here for. Lads, see no one bothers us.” The Captain ordered gesturing Kyri to go inside, smiling slightly as she deferred and let him enter first.<br>
<br>
“Ah, very wise, you are, you’ve just met me so who knows what I may have set up inside for you if you went first. Indeed, this shows me you’re the one I’m looking for.” Osaftars said agreeably.<br>
<br>
“Spare the flattery,” Kyri replied, “just tell me what you want and how much you’re paying me to do it. I think I know but it’s always best for the potential employer to come out and say it himself.”<br>
<br>
“Blunt and to the point, I can deal with that well enough.” Osaftars replied. “Very well, to be ‘blunt’ you are correct in assuming I need a hired killer to remove my competition here. I seek to rule the Council and bring it under my control to increase our plundering ability far beyond what we now accomplish due to those timid wolf pups. To do so I must remove the most senior of them, Captain Bloodspear. Once Bloodspear is taken care of the others will follow my lead.”<br>
<br>
“Sounds simple enough.” Kyri replied, “So why go so far from here to get someone to do the job? I’d think some of your ‘lads’ could take care of this.”<br>
<br>
“Why? Because if one of mine were seen committing the deed, the other Captains would turn on me in an instant and bring me down. No I need someone who can not be traced back to me and mine to do this. If you are killed my hands are clean to try again. If you succeed then you will be paid and we go our separate ways, until the next time I need to hire your services.”<br>
<br>
“And speaking of hire,” Kyri said, “how much are you offering, you seem to have forgotten that part.”<br>
<br>
“Ah yes, how does this do for payment?” Osaftars answered opening the chest and revealing a velium chain necklace studded with a dozen blue diamonds. “This little trinket was picked up a few weeks back during a raid on a merchant’s ship. It would be impossible to fence here but in a far away land? It would sell for quite a bit I would imagine.” Smiling at the end as he saw Kyri looking greedily at the revealed treasure.<br>
<br>
“That’s quite a bit for such a simple job.” Kyri said after finally looking up from the necklace having quickly estimated its worth. “What’s the catch?”<br>
<br>
Looking surprised, Osaftars assured her, “No catches, I can easily make this up once I rule the Council, and such a prize will ensure you will do your best to pull off the job won’t it?”<br>
<br>
“Ok fine you have a deal,” Kyri agreed, “I take out your competitor and you give me the necklace.” Pausing briefly in thought she added, “Is there any particular way you want it done? To send a message or something to the others?”<br>
<br>
Smiling again the Captain reached into a drawer and pulled out a small vial. “Something I am sure you’ve run across, a slow acting poison, dump the whole vial’s contents into the mess pot of the Oceancrasher- that’s Bloodspear’s ship, once he and his crew finish their meal they’ll find themselves dead in a couple hours. A fine little concoction put together in Cabilis, many odd plants there, whose liquefied essences have the most interesting effects. None of my people are skilled enough to get in and out of that ship undetected or we’d have done it already. So that’s where you come in. Assuming you CAN do it of course.”<br>
<br>
“Don’t worry about that,” Kyri retorted, “I can do that no problem, just keep that necklace safe for when I come back. But now if you don’t want us connected how are you going to explain my being here now- lots of people have seen me on the dock here today.”<br>
<br>
“Ah a simple matter.” Osaftars said dismissively, “my lads know what’s afoot, they’re spinning tales about a Teir-dal merchant looking to hire us to raid a competitor. It’s happened several times in the past, once more won’t cause any additional interest. Of course it does tend to be a slow process, as you’ve noticed we don’t much care for outsiders here so there are many intermediate steps before such a meeting. You being here merely means the job is almost sealed. No one will think twice about your presence for a few days as we ‘finalize’ our ‘deal’ here. “<br>
<br>
“Ok then,” Kyri agreed taking the vial offered, “I’m not too fond of staying long in a place where most folk would rather slit my throat than let me buy breakfast. Tomorrow night, then- one day to scout out the ship and one to slip into the mess hall and season their dinner. I’ll be back here at midnight for my pay, since if this stuff works they’ll all be dead by then.”<br>
<br>
“Excellent, until tomorrow night then, enjoy your hunt. But for now I must get back to my work. You know the way out. May Cazic smile on your mission.” Osaftars replied as he returned to the task he had been interrupted at.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Arrogant lizard</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought as once more an iksar dismissed her like a lackey. Still annoyed she, escorted now by one of the two crewmen who brought her here, made her way off the ship and headed back to the inn to rest up before she began her scouting that night.<br>
<br>
The other iksar waited until Kyri was out of sight before entering his Captain’s room. As Osaftars looked up, the crewman asked, “Well did she take the job?”<br>
<br>
Pushing aside his work Osaftars replied, “Of course, these softskins are easily moved by wealth. She has taken the job. Perhaps this one might succeed, she has some basic common sense for a softskin when not distracted by wealth.”<br>
<br>
“And if she does, you’re going to give her THAT necklace?” the crewman questioned.<br>
<br>
“Of course not, don’t be a fool.” Osaftars snapped, “If this one actually does succeed she might one day be hired to deal with ME. So if this assassin is successful we shall have to take steps to prevent such an occurrence from taking place and ensure my own rise to power occurs with no complications.”<br>
<br>
Reaching into a second drawer, Osaftars removed a pouch filled with a fine gray powder and ran his claws through it before addressing his crewman again. “Cazic’s gift will take care of everything.”<br>
<br>
