<br>
   Absently fingering the vial of poison in her pouch, Kyri considered her options. A frontal approach was folley, the crew would never let her get near the messpot as an outsider. Besides anyone here would be willing to slit anyone's throat for so much as looking at them oddly, nevermind a stranger waltzing on board their ship. <br>
<br>
   A night approach would be her preferred method but that would have her arriving after the meals and force her to leave the poison out for hours before someone MIGHT decide to use whatever it was she poisoned. No, she concluded, she only had a few hours to get inside and &quot;season&quot; the meal. This time a disguise would have to be trusted and the opportunity taken if one came to her.<br>
<br>
    According to Osaftars, the cook and his helpers often left the ship a few hours before dusk to gather what was needed for the evening meal. That would be when she had to strike.<br>
<br>
   Kyri returned to her quarters where her few belongings remained. On the job she always travelled light just in case she needed to make a hasty depature and didn't want to leave anything of value behind. The temptation to come back for something with sentimental value has proven to be a fatal error for many novices of the trade. The new arrival right before a mysterious death was always the remembered one when the questions started.<br>
<br>
   Going through the one bag she brought with her, Kyri unpacked some plain, unadorned clothes. The long sleeved tunic and pants of a common laborer with the large woolen hooded cloak to go over it, and provide cover for her weapons as well. Even in a place like this brandishing weapons openly was a good way to get in trouble. Better to &quot;privately&quot; convince any footpads lurking about that easier prey lay elsewhere.<br>
<br>
    Leaving the room, Kyri made sure to check her wristband where the tiny springlocked needle lay, coated with a special &quot;rustproofing&quot; experiment of hers. A flick of the wrist would trigger the spring to shoot the needle out with enough force to pierce the skin of her target before retracting- though she had to basically be touching the person to reach them as the spring and needle were not very large. The poison on the needle would be enough to make a person grow faint and fall unconscious for a few hours or so. Long enough to rob them of everything of value while &quot;helping&quot; them. Today the purpose will be slightly different.<br>
<br>
   She made her way to the market area of the harbor town and found a place to wait near the food vendors, occasionally purchasing something to snack on to give her a reason to be there. Kyri smiled to herself as she saw the market was rather crowded, many people brushing up against each other unavoidably. If she was so inclinced, Kyri could have certainly been able to rob many of the people present under these circumstances but she was not hear for that.<br>
<br>
   Finally, just as Osaftars predicted the cook and a couple of servants began loudly making their way to the market. The cook, a shrilled voiced fellow, could be heard clearly arguing prices with the vendors about how &quot;Captain Bloodspear will hear of this outrage!&quot; a common phrase as the haggling began. Kyri did note the vendors did not haggle quite so forcefully after such announcements and grudgingly gave the cook some credit for wits.<br>
<br>
   As they moved along, the cook continued his purchases, and began to load up the servants with him with bags and containers to be used for the meal. Finally after an hour or so the cook announced that it was time to prepare the meal now and obediently the servants turned and began to follow him back to the boat. <br>
<br>
   Kyri had in the meantime been able to make her way near the trio as they haggled, feigning interest in a nearby artists paintings. Seeing the moment, Kyri stepped out after them and came near when she suddenly stumbled and fell forward, her arms reaching out for the nearest source of support, cooincidently the rearmost of the cook's servants. As her hands made contact, Kyri flicked her wrist and smiled as she saw the servant stiffen briefly as the needle struck home and retracted back under her wristband before anyone could notice.<br>
<br>
   &quot;My apologies,&quot; Kyri muttered as the servant tried to hold onto everything without spilling it and keep his balance at the same time. As the poison seeped into his blood , the servant began to get weak kneed as the cook turned around and saw him lagging behind him.<br>
<br>
   &quot;Hurry up you...what are you doing!&quot; the cook demanded as the servant lost hisbattle with the poison and collapsed to the ground. Kyri, still standing near &quot;helpfully&quot; caught some of the bags the servant had been carrying as he fell.<br>
<br>
   &quot;What happened?&quot; the cook demanded to Kyri as people began to move away from the fallen figure lest they get caught in some sort of feud.<br>
<br>
   &quot;I'm not sure.&quot; Kyri answered, &quot;I lost my balance and near tripped if your friend here hadn't been standing so close for me to grab on to. I was afraid i'd make him drop everything he had on him but he seemed like he had everything under control. Then he took a few steps and just fell over. I tried to catch some of what he had with him so it wouldn't be damaged but that i'm afraid i missed a few things.&quot; she concluded pointing to the bags laying on the ground, vegetables spilling from one bag that burst open on impact.<br>
<br>
    Glaring down at the fallen servant, the cook snarled &quot;That lazy fool must have been drunk again. I warned him about drinking before the meal is done. The captain will have my head if his meal is late and thanks to this drunken oaf i'll never be able to get everything back to the ship in time!&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;The captain?&quot; Kyri asked innocently, &quot;you mean you work for one of the Captains?&quot; she finished wide eyed<br>
<br>
   Sensing her awe, the cook straighetened and replied proudly &quot;That's right, I serve Captain Bloodspear, the meanest, roughest and most successful of all the Captains here. Though if i don't get his dinner cooking he'll hang me by my thumbs from the mast and leave me there for a week.&quot; he finished trying to gather the fallen bags when Kyri knelt down beside him also gathering the bags and added. &quot;Oh please, let me help you, i'd be honored to offer any help i could for such a mighty captain. This way you won;t be late, my mother said i have some skill in the kitchens myself, i could help.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Eyeing her carefully the cook said &quot;Well, that drunkard will be of no use to me, let him stew in his own juices here in the street, maybe when he sobers up he might actually still have his clothes. I have no choice come along you...what did you say your name was again?&quot;<br>
<br>
  &quot;Sumida.&quot; Kyri replied, deciding to get yet another jab at a Hateborn in case anything went wrong.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Good enough then Sumida, come along and hurry.&quot; the cook replied as Kyri took up the servant's load and joined the small procession back to the ship.<br>
<br>
   The crew looked at her oddly as Kyri was most certainly not the man who left with the cook but the exasperated cook- whom Kyri finally learned was named Marty- argued them down by saying if the captain's supper was late then he knew who to say was holding him up from starting the meal.<br>
<br>
   Soon enough Kyri made it to the kitchen where Marty began passing orders to the staff there who went into a frenzy of activity as they were already behind schedule. Kyri did her part- though she was in fact no great cook by any means but it didn't take much skill to chop up vegetables for the stew the cook decided was the only thing that they might finish in time. She also sought the chance to add the poison to the dish but found Marty often tasted the dish to be sure it was cooking properly so she had to delay.<br>
<br>
   Finally as the stew was nearly finished she found her chance as Marty told her to add some water to the stew which was becoming thicker than the Captain preferred. making sure no one noticed, Kyri quickly dumped the vial's contents into the water she was adding. Fortunately it was colorless and thus undetectable as she poured the poisoned water into the stew. <br>
<br>
   A short time later Marty did taste the stew once more and announced it being satisfactory. Idly Kyri hoped the poison was slow acting since marty's turning green and keeling over dead would put a crimp in her plans. She was about to leave when Marty insisted she help serve the crew as they were still shorthanded. Seeing no reasonable way to refuse and not arouse suspicion, Kyri relented. Smiling for the first time since she met him, Marty promised to have a big bowl of stew set aside for her as well when she finished serving the others- since she did put in the effort to help make it...and save Marty's tender skin in the process, it was only fair that she at least get a free meal out of it.<br>
<br>
   As she expected, the crew was half drunk and were part octopus as she unsuccessfully tried to avoid their pinches and slaps on her buttocks. One tried to draw her into his embrace and found himself wearing the contents of his bowl, and laying on his back as Kyri kicked his chair out from under him-to the laughter of his comrades who then treated Kyri as one of their own...after a fashion.<br>
<br>
   Once the last was served, she returned to the kitchen where Marty appeared a bit pale. &quot;Good job Sumida, the boys are like that, but i see you know how to handle yourself. I think all this stress has gotten me a bit under the weather though. Anyway i set some stew aside for you. Go eat while its still warm.&quot; he encouraged.<br>
<br>
   &quot;In a minute.&quot; Kyri answered, &quot;I just need to get some air for a bit, it is a bit warm in here from all the cooking after all. And my stomach needs to settle some&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;Of course, of course.&quot; Marty replied &quot;I forgot you're a lubber and not a seadog like the rest of us. Go on ahead, no one will bother you.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Before he changed his mind, Kyri nodded her thanks and made her way topside. Of course once she got there she continued on off the ship. The drunken guards on the watch never even stirred as she crept past them and made her way back into the city, where she disappeared into the night.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Well that should do it, from the way Marty was acting from just a taste i think that ship will have maybe an hour before the poison kicks in completely. Now i just have to wait and see how effective this poison of Osaftars really is.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought to herself as she returned to her rooms. Tossing her cloak- which was stolen anyway, into one of the alleys just in case anyone remembered the cloaked woman from the market.<br>
<br>
   The next morning Kyri went down, in her regular armor to breakfast in the commons area and found the innkeeper going on about the Oceancrasher's entire crew being found dead in the mess hall.Feigning ignorance, Kyri asked for a few details but the innkeeper claimed he knew little else. <br>
<br>
   &quot;A servant of some sort who had passed out in an alleyway and robbed of everything but his loincloth went back to the ship and started shouting about everyone was dead. A few folk went back with him and sure enough the whole crew from the Captain on down was dead. No one knows who's responsible&quot; he told her before someone else walked into the inn and he began the story over from the beginning.<br>
<br>
  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Looks like i'll be getting paid then, that necklace will get me a good price, i'm sure Stanos can get rid of it.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> Kyri thought as she finished her breakfast and made her way towards the Stormwave.<br>
<br>
   Showing her note of passage to the guards, got her invited to Osaftar's cabin where the iksar pirate was waiting.<br>
<br>
   &quot;Well done. The news of this tragic accident has been the talk of the harbor this morning. No doubt the people will be looking for someone else to show them the way after the tragic loss of Captain Bloodspear.&quot; Osaftars greeted her as she enetered and offfered her a seat<br>
<br>
   &quot;Yeah i'm sure they will,&quot; Kyri replied drily, as she sat adding, &quot;and i'm sure you know the perfect candidate for the job. But that's your affair. All i'm worried about is my pay.&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;Ah yes, right to the point aren't you?&quot; Osaftars replied calling for the Bo'sun who was then sent off to fetch the necklace. Turning back to Kyri he took two mugs off the shelf, placing them on the table before them and then took a bottle of wine as well.<br>
<br>
   &quot;While we wait for your payment to arrive perhaps you'll join me in a celebratory drink?&quot; the iksar asked pouring the wine in one of the cups. As he turned to pour into Kyri's she surprised him by taking the bottle from his hands.<br>
<br>
  &quot;Allow me.&quot; Kyri asked as she sniffed the contents within cautiously as if looking for something.<br>
<br>
   &quot;Cautious as ever i see.&quot; Osaftrars replied once he realized what Kyri was up to. &quot;But not necessary, after all had i wished you dead i would not allow you to come within a blade's reach of me. I'd have my men shoot down down before you set foot on this ship.&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;Maybe,&quot; Kyri answered as she filled her mug, not being able to pick up the scent of any poison within the wine. &quot;then again who knows what tricks you might have.&quot; she finished dipping a finger into the cup and tasting it with the tip of her tongue and waited for any sign of something toxic to appear as such a small dose would not incapacitate her.<br>
<br>
  &quot;You softskins.&quot; Osaftars smiled shaking his head. Here allow me to set your fears aside.&quot; and took a deep drink from his own mug. Placing it back on the table the pirate said &quot;See I still breathe, you have nothing to fear from the wine.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Waiting a moment even then Kyri looked for a sign of discomfort in her drinking partner before taking a drink from her own mug and with a surprise discovering it to be a rather high quality vintage. As Osaftars smiled, the Bo'sun took that moment to return with the case containing the necklace.<br>
<br>
   &quot;Ah excellent.&quot; the Captain replied as he openned the case and showed the necklace to Kyri to prove it was really there. As she reached for it, Osaftars closed the case and pulled it out of her reach saying &quot;OF course this is not for you.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Surprised, Kyri came to her feet only to find her balance was off as she drew her ragebringer. &quot;What...&quot; she began as the iksar smiled grimly.<br>
<br>
   &quot;Fool of a softskin, did you think i would give such a valuable object to one such as you?&quot; Osaftars sneered as Kyri used her free hand to support herself upright on the table. As she looked accusingly at the pirate he went on, &quot;Oh yes the wine is as i said a fine vintage, not to be ruind with a poison, your mug however, was coated with a drug which shall render you unconscious shortly.&quot;<br>
<br>
   Her hand sliding off the table, Kyri dropped her ragebringer as her hands would not obey her commands and slumped to her knees as the iksar continued. &quot;You have only yourself to blame you know. You were the first to actually succeed in this task and so you are much too dangerous to be running around on your own. Besides there are other captains to be dealt with here and your services will be required do deal with them as well. Obviously no iksar will treat with such as you on an equal basis so consider this to be the first part of new new life in the service of the Empire... as its slave.&quot; he finished as Kyri slumped unconscious to the cabin floor.<br>
<br>
   Waiting a moment to ensure she was indeed unconscious, Osaftars reached into the second drawer of his table and pulled out the pouch holding the grey powder known as &quot;Cazic's gift&quot;. Taking a pinch he placed it into the mug Kyri had drank from and with the Bo'sun's help he forced Kyri to reflexively swallow a few more sips of the doctored wine.<br>
<br>
   &quot;That will be enough for now.&quot; Osaftars replied setting the mug aside. Gesturing to the Bo'sun he added, &quot;Take her down below to the hold where we keep the slaves, remove anything that might be used as a weapon and leave here there. Once she awakens we shall begin the next phase of my plan.&quot;<br>
<br>
   &quot;Aye Cap'n&quot; the bo'sun replied calling for another of the sailors to drag Kyri's body down below. As they departed Osaftars smiled to himself as he thought. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Very soon now, not only will i be head of the Council of Five, now four thanks to the assassin, but the entire fleet shall be mine for the glory of the Empire. And its foes shall tremble at our passing. All that is needed now is to bend the assassin to my will and let her be my hand of death against those who oppose me.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> patting the pouch sitting on the table before him he concluded <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>And Cazic's gift shall provide me the way.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
