<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp The room was dark but that was no real obstacle to her night vision. Looking at herself, Kyri realized she had been stripped down to her tismak undergarmets, no sign of a weapon or anything that could be used to pick the shackle’s locks holding her in place. The room was bare except for a bowl filled with what appeared to be water. After the last drink however, Kyri was not about to be so foolish as to trust another drink that Osaftars might provide.<br>
<br>
&nbsp &nbsp &nbsp &nbsp As she struggled to her knees, still a bit lightheaded from the drugged, she heard a commotion from above her. Apparently she had been watched for the time that she would come to, for only minutes later a hatch across the room opened and two figures came down the stairway towards her. <br>
<br>
Osaftars looked at his captive curiously as he neared Kyri, stopping a few feet in front of her as she glared up at him. “What do you think you’re doing?” Kyri snarled defiantly as he looked down at her. “We had a deal!”<br>
<br>
The iksar captain looked at her oddly and answered “A deal? With a slave? The Empire makes no such deals.”<br>
<br>
“Well if I find a slave I’ll be sure to let them know that.” Kyri retorted, “I killed your rival like we agreed, so stop playing your games and pay me and I’ll pretend this never happened.” She finished bluffing, as Osaftars held all the advantages right now.<br>
<br>
“Fool!” Osaftars sneered, “Did you actually think that was my sole agenda? Having one such as you come halfway across the world just to kill someone here? Your arrogance is even greater than I expected slave.”<br>
<br>
“I told you…” Kyri began, stopping as the crewman accompanying the captain smacked her across the face at a nod from his Captain. As she spun back seething Osaftars continued, “Do not interrupt your betters. Now since you won’t be going anywhere I can tell you what my real purpose is. If you interrupt you will be punished for your insolence understood?” Seething Kyri weighed the odds and abruptly nodded in disgust.<br>
<br>
“Excellent, you are already beginning to learn.” Osaftars complimented her, “Now while indeed my rise to rule the council here and control the pirating efforts for the glory of the Empire is indeed one goal of mine. There is another service I provide for the Empire.”<br>
<br>
“You see,” he continued, “Unlike these radicals who seek to join with outsiders against the foes of the Empire, too ignorant to see that ALL are our enemies, I have a duty to protect the Empire and its citizens. That being the case I heard the rumors of those guards who could be bribed into convincing the rest of the city to accept the presence of outsiders. They will be dealt with when the time comes, such weakness disgraces the memories of the Emperors past. An even greater threat I realized came from those skilled in the art of murder, such as yourself. These softskins might prove to be a threat of their own against the Empire. Think about it, no need to sneak through the streets fearful of discovery and death when the citizens have been bribed into letting these softskins walk the streets openly.”<br>
<br>
“Those fools who guard the city would let you wander where you wish, perhaps even to the chambers of the leaders of the Empire, to foully murder them while they slept, which is a softskin tradition I have heard, of those too cowardly or fearful to challenge an Imperial citizen in a fair fight. So this threat had to be dealt with, before everyone’s eyes were blinded or numbed by the presence of your kind among us.”<br>
<br>
“That when I decided I must act. So I left the message with the Haggle Baron knowing full well, only those who could enter the city could read it, and that only those trained in the art of murder would come here. In doing so I could achieve both goals. To first improve my station here and use the power of a united pirate force for the Empire’s glory. Secondly I could remove the chance for killers like yourself to bring harm to the Empire, by removing you from play.” <br>
<br>
“You should feel honored softskin, four others before you came here, all were slain before they could complete their mission. You were the first to succeed, proving my point of your threat. It could have just as easily been the Court of Pain which you struck down, but instead you aid my rise to power and have been neutralized as a threat against the Empire. As a reward for your success, I will not kill you, that could have been easily done once you were unconscious, for you may still serve the Empire even now. As a slave of course, the only role suitable for you softskins at any rate, but still an honor that one of the Empire sees your value enough to keep you. Indeed, you shall eliminate the other three captains here as well, to ensure my supremacy of the harbor. With the others dead, no one will be able to challenge me.”<br>
<br>
“Of course once you have finished your mission, you will be sent to Cabilis to work in the mines for the rest of your days, unless someone else desires your talents in the Empire’s service. A fitting role for one of your ilk indeed.” Osaftars concluded.<br>
<br>
“Oh just like that eh?” Kyri replied, “On your say so I’m going to be a good little slave and do what you want? I don’t think that’s going to happen. Has it ever occurred to you that I might walk the streets there because I wish to aid the Empire?”<br>
<br>
“Then you should have no worries then,” Osaftars answered, “for aid the Empire you shall in your slavery and it will be grateful for your service. As for the rest, your kind are among the more stubborn of the softskins but I am confident you will accept your place soon enough. Cazic’s gift can control even the strongest of wills.” He concluded, lifting the bowl of water up and taking a drink as Kyri’s eyes followed the gesture, which did not go unnoticed.<br>
<br>
“Ah thirsty are you?” Osaftars asked, holding the bowl to her lips, “ That drug I used does have that after effect I have noticed, then drink, as you can see, I have drunk and I feel quite fine.”<br>
<br>
Suspiscious still, Kyri looked away only to have the crewman grab her head and yanked it back towards the bowl.<br>
<br>
“Drink.” Osaftars demanded, as the crewman grabbed her jaw and hair and with a yank opened her mouth so Osaftars could pour the water down her throat.<br>
<br>
Spluttering and choking as she tried not to swallow, Kyri found some of the water did indeed get swallowed reflexively and glared at Osaftars again.<br>
<br>
“Good enough for now.” Osaftars decided after a few gulps were forced down her throat and placing the rest of the bowl in her reach on the floor. “Come we have work to do.” He said gesturing to the crewman who released Kyri before adding “Feel free to drink as much as you wish, there is plenty more. Food will be brought later because I do not wish to have you weak from hunger when it comes time to perform your service for the Empire.”<br>
<br>
Getting her coughing under control, Kyri spat at Osaftars’ feet and snarled, “You’re dead lizard, trust me.”<br>
<br>
Looking back with a serpentine smile Osaftars answered, “I think not slave, trust ME.” And left the cargo bay.<br>
<br>
Kyri glared at the doorway for a brief time and then looked down at the half full bowl of water before her. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Obviously there’s something wrong with that water, he seemed awfully pleased when they managed to pour it down my throat.Not sure what though, my throat’s still dry but other than that, I just feel...normal. </em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She debated whether to knock over the remainder of the water but decided against it in case that was supposed to last her through the day. While Osaftars did insist that she be fed enough to finish killing off his fellow captains he made no mention of how often that would be. Plus the cargo bay was rather warm and dehydration was something to keep in mind as well she realized.<br>
<br>
Testing the chains once more, Kyri gathered herself into as comfortable a posisiton as she could while she waited. Nothing else could be done at that time. As she sat there, her body grew oddly relaxed despite the somewhat awkward posisition she was force to kneel in. Her throughs drifted from escape, to pleasant daydreams of untold riches. After a time she forgot her bonds and tried stretching out as she felt an unnatural laziness seep into her muscles, only to be brought up short. As her body languished, Kyri lay herself down as best she could and closed her eyes indulging in her body’s reaction.<br>
<br>
Kyri openned her eyes some time later and realized she had been still for so long that she had stiffened up and had gotten slightly numb in the process. Trying to strech out and get feeling back in her limbs she found herself dry mouthed again and found herself looking at the bowl of water again. Again she tore her eyes from it, not quite trusting the water but her thrist would not be forgotten. No one else had come to see her, and the noises above her from the crew attending to their duties did little to distract her and soon she found herself staring at the bowl as her tongue felt leaden in her mouth. Her stubbornness endured for nearly an hour before she finally broke down and drank deeply from the bowl again, as she reasoned it hadn’t killed her yet so it was probably safe. <br>
<br>
She then placed the empty bowl down with a sigh of relief as her parched mouth welcomed the moisture. Hoping someone would come by with something to eat, for her stomach told her it was indeed time for some sort of meal, Kyri decided to call out, “Hey you think someone can get around to bringing me something to eat down here?”<br>
<br>
Laughter answered her shout which was about what she expected she admitted to herself. Still, that lizard’s lied to me once already, who knows, maybe he does plan on starving me. If that’s the case I’d better start planning. As she began her planning, she idly noticed her body again relaxing as she sat there and her thoughts again began to drift as she had to force herelf to concentrate on the matter at hand. <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>What’s wrong with me, I can’t keep my thoughts straight. Is there something in the water after all? But this doesn’t seem to be anything bad,just a relaxant, it doesn’t make sense.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> She wondered before more pleasant thoughts intruded and she lay back down on the deck in relaxing bliss.<br>
<br>
Osaftars opened the hold with a tray of bread, cheese and water in hand to bring to his slave. As he reached Kyri he found the Teir-dal lying on the deck a faint smile on her face as she lay there unaware of her surroundings. Smiling to himself Osaftars thought as he placed the tray nearby and in reach of his still unwilling slave, <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Cazic’s gift does its work well. With no apparent side effects the victim relishes its relaxing effect and will slowly grow to want it more often. As a thief- she may have the wit to realize there’s something in her drink but that won’t help her, the dryness it leaves encourages its victims to quench their thirst and so continue the cycle. Of course, it does not affect an iksar in any way, only the softskins as the shamans have proven, so my drinking from the bowl earlier convinced my slave of its harmlessness. The fool. When she awakens she will be thirsty again and everything on this tray has been dosed with a sprinkling of Cazic’s gift to make its hold on her even stronger. A few more days and its hold on her will be complete. Then she shall see what happens when she is deprived of its “benefits” and once that is made clear then she will be MINE! For the glory of the EMPIRE!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
With a smile, Osaftars looked down at the resting Teir-dal being slowly brought into his service unbeknownst to her, turned and went back above deck.<br>
